docs.abstract: Over nearly 70 years, a Brooklyn-born entrepreneur introduced French brands to Americans and cultivated Rhone Valley vines in a West Coast winery.
docs.snippet: Over nearly 70 years, a Brooklyn-born entrepreneur introduced French brands to Americans and cultivated Rhone Valley vines in a West Coast winery.
docs.lead_paragraph: On the day Prohibition was repealed in 1933, Sidney Haas was the 12th applicant (and, the family says, the first independent store owner) licensed by New York State to legally sell alcoholic beverages. He proceeded to transform the Manhattan butcher shop founded by his uncle, Morris Lehmann, who had immigrated from Germany in 1870, into a wine and liquor store.

headline.main: Robert Haas, Wine Importer and California Vintner, Dies at 90
headline.print_headline: Robert Haas, 90, Wine Connoisseur  Was an Importer and a California Vintner

docs.abstract: It’s time to stop using technology and the internet as though you were shopping at a supermarket.
docs.snippet: It’s time to stop using technology and the internet as though you were shopping at a supermarket.
docs.lead_paragraph: If there was one broad takeaway from the data leak involving Cambridge Analytica, the voter profiling firm that obtained private information from up to 87 million Facebook accounts, it’s that you should hesitate before sharing your data with an unknown brand.

headline.main: Unknown Tech Brands Aren’t Like Groceries. Don’t Just Grab Them.
headline.print_headline: To Protect Data, Be Wary of Unfamiliar Brands
